ucose and fructose","Converts maltose into two glucose molecules","Breaks down cellulose into glucose molecules"],"correctOptions":[1],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EPancreatic amylase breaks down starch into maltose, maltotriose and alpha-limit dextrins\u003C/strong\u003E in the small intestine. This is a crucial step in carbohydrate digestion that follows initial starch breakdown by salivary amylase in the mouth.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe incorrect options can be explained:\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cul\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EConverting lactose into glucose and galactose\u003C/strong\u003E is performed by lactase, a brush border enzyme\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EBreaking down sucrose into glucose and fructose\u003C/strong\u003E is performed by sucrase, a brush border enzyme\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EConverting maltose into glucose molecules\u003C/strong\u003E is performed by maltase, a brush border enzyme\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EBreaking down cellulose into glucose molecules\u003C/strong\u003E cannot be performed by human digestive enzymes\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ul\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe products of pancreatic amylase digestion require further processing by brush border enzymes to produce absorbable monosaccharides. These final products - glucose, galactose and fructose - are then absorbed via specific transporters in the small intestine.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Pancreatic amylase breaks down starch into maltose, maltotriose and alpha-limit dextrins in the small intestine.","Brush border enzymes complete carbohydrate digestion by breaking down disaccharides into monosaccharides.","The final products of carbohydrate digestion are glucose, galactose and fructose."],"references":["Tortora GJ, Derrickson BH, Burkett B, Peoples G, Dye D, Cooke J, et al. Principles of Anatomy and Physiology, 2nd Asia-Pacific Edition: 